## 9. Occupational Health and Safety (OHS) Integration

- **Governance:** Women’s Safety Steering Committee co-chaired by MD/CEO and Senior HSE Manager (female). Female HSE Champions per shift; stop-work authority.
- **Risk Management:** JSA, P2W, LOTO, WAH, confined space, lifting, traffic, ergonomics, fatigue and heat stress.
- **Training:** Induction; quarterly refreshers; monthly Safe Hands Workshops led by female facilitators; certification support (NEBOSH/OSHA).
- **KPIs:** LTIR ≤ 0.5 per 200,000 hours; near-miss reports doubled; female HSE leaders ≥ 40% within 18 months.
- **Incident Management:** 24-hour reporting; 72-hour RCA; lessons learned; corrective action tracking.
- **Emergency Response:** 24/7 ERT; ERP drills; spill response with NOSDRA protocols.

---

## 10. Stakeholder Engagement and Disclosure

- **Stakeholders:** FMEnv, LASEPA, NPA, NIMASA, NOSDRA; local communities near Ikorodu terminal; workers/contractors; emergency services; civil society and trade associations.
- **Methods:** Scoping and focus group meetings (including women-only sessions); public notices; terminal noticeboards; non-technical summary in English and Yoruba; grievance channels (hotline/email/suggestion boxes).
- **Inclusive Engagement:** Time/place accessible to women and vulnerable groups; privacy options; use of local languages as needed.
- **Disclosure:** ESIA and non-technical summary available digitally and on-site.

---

## 11. Grievance Redress Mechanism (GRM)

- **Principles:** Accessible, transparent, confidential, non-retaliatory, gender-sensitive.
- **Channels:** Hotline (handled by GK & A), email (gkandalogistics@gmail.com), suggestion boxes at the gatehouse and admin office, in-person to supervisors or HSE.
- **Process:** Acknowledge within 3 business days; assess and investigate within 15 business days; resolve and communicate within 30 business days; appeal to Steering Committee/MD if needed.
- **Worker GRM:** Separate HR-led channel with anonymity options.
- **GBV/SEA Pathway:** Confidential intake by trained female officer; survivor-centered approach; referral to appropriate service providers as requested by survivor.

---

## 12. Emergency Preparedness and Response (ERP)

- **Risks:** Fire, spill, medical emergencies, severe weather, security threats.
- **Structure:** Incident Commander; HSE Manager; ERT Lead (female); functional teams; liaison with NPA/NIMASA/NOSDRA/Lagos State Fire Service/Hospitals.
- **Equipment:** Fire extinguishers, spill kits/booms, first-aid stations, alarms, PPE, communication devices.
- **Procedures:** Muster points and evacuation routes clearly marked; quarterly drills; bi-annual multi-agency exercises; after-action reviews.
- **Contacts:** National Emergency Number 112; Lagos Emergency 767; internal duty contacts maintained 24/7 by GK & A HSE.

---

## 13. Climate Change, GHG and Resilience

- **GHG Sources:** Diesel equipment, generators, marine fuels, grid electricity.
- **Approach:** Annual scope 1 and 2 accounting using activity data and recognized emission factors; qualitative review of scope 3 where feasible.
- **Reduction Measures:** Maintenance; anti-idling; equipment upgrades; LED lighting; explore electrification/shore power options if feasible.
- **Resilience:** Flood/storm surge preparedness; improved drainage and elevated control panels; severe weather protocols.

